<section id="directories">

<title>Directories</title>

<para>The standard installation procedure creates up to four directories:</para>

<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>The <firstterm>installation directory</firstterm>
contains the installed files of the &MiKTeX; distribution.
<indexterm>
<primary>installation directory</primary>
<secondary>defined</secondary>
</indexterm>
The default directory location
is <filename>&installdir;</filename>.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>The <firstterm>user configuration directory</firstterm>
<indexterm>
<primary>user configuration directory</primary>
<secondary>defined</secondary>
</indexterm>
contains user-specific configuration files.
The default directory location
is <filename>&userconfigdir;</filename>.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>The <firstterm>user data directory</firstterm>
<indexterm>
<primary>user data directory</primary>
<secondary>defined</secondary>
</indexterm>
contains user-specific data files.
The default directory location
is <filename>&userdatadir;</filename>.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>The <firstterm>common configuration &amp; data directory</firstterm>
<indexterm>
<primary>common configuration directory</primary>
<secondary>defined</secondary>
</indexterm>
<indexterm>
<primary>common data directory</primary>
<secondary>defined</secondary>
</indexterm>
contains common configuration and data files.
The default directory location
is <filename>&commondatadir;</filename>.</para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>

<para>It is possible to integrate additional directories into a
&MiKTeX; setup. For example, users often want to
maintain a separate directory with their own style files. See <xref
linkend="rootmanager"/>, for more information how to manage this.</para>

</section>

